{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b2e350b1-739a-4db7-9020-e7e94492b8f5","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files) when a process crashes. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`. Sort by date to find the latest:\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n> **Tip:** If you need a full core dump instead, set `ulimit -c unlimited` *before* launching the app. Core dumps go to `/cores/core.<pid>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ad35bfb-a9df-4105-b6c9-2a3725cc91a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic question about macOS crash reporting, not a code task.","outputTokens":277,"requestId":"D810:1DC1AD:6247D61:6A24808:69FBEFE0"},"id":"31659681-205b-45d3-a578-9479f685c217","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:50:33.287Z","parentId":"8f58ae7f-728e-40ad-85c4-d04bf81562a4"}
